[Event "Baker Bridge - Minor Suit Openings"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "2"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "S:KT4.J97.AK72.K53 Q62.Q42.43.QJT87 AJ5.KT6.Q986.A96 9873.A853.JT5.42"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
1D pass 2NT pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 2, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "d372841fd5a548e83265cb58f01e158bef6addd6c1f7efacc9fbd5d9aaa94569"]
[Category "Basic Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "basic_bidding/minor_suit_openings"]
[Student "S"]
{You have two very good choices, neither of which is really wrong. You could bid 2NT, showing 13-16 points, balanced, or you could bid 3\D, showing 13-16 points, good trump support.

What should decide you is the bidding priorities. You'd much rather try to play a 9-trick game than an 11-trick game. And at the same time you must trust your partner not to leave you hung out in Notrump with an unsuitable hand. (Can you believe I wrote Notrump and unsuitable in the same sentence?)

Anyway, you bid 2NT and partner raises to 3NT.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "W:AK92.J5.K72.K832 J754.97432.J3.A6 T83.KQT6.AQ6.QJ5 Q6.A8.T9854.T974"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
1C pass 1H pass 1S pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "341b8767c8d9bd3ae7f6267d18342607a7831e755ff0132c1aca491863f9f498"]
[Category "Basic Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "basic_bidding/minor_suit_openings"]
[Student "S"]
{With 14 points and a 4-3-3-3 distribution this could be the perfect hand for a jump to 2NT. But not when the 4-card suit is a Major - you should not skip bidding a Major when you have the opportunity.

So you respond 1\H. Partner says 1\S.  

Partner doesn't have 4 \Hs so you go back to thinking this is an ideal notrump hand. So ideal that you apply the "She who knows, goes" principle and bid 3NT. Partner smiles and passes.}

